  "prompt": "If light has no mass, how can a solar sail be propelled?",
  "response": "The propulsion of a solar sail is based on the principle of momentum transfer from photons (particles of light) to the sail. Although photons have no mass, they do carry momentum due to their energy and motion. When photons strike the reflective surface of a solar sail, they transfer their momentum to the sail, creating a small force that propels the sail forward.\n\nThis phenomenon is known as radiation pressure. The force exerted on the sail is relatively small, but in the vacuum of space, where there is no friction or resistance, even a small continuous force can result in significant acceleration over time.\n\nSolar sails are typically large and lightweight to maximize the effect of radiation pressure. As the sail reflects the photons, the momentum transfer is more efficient, resulting in greater propulsion. By angling the sail correctly, the direction of the force can be controlled, allowing the sail to navigate through space.",
